{"cursor":"2077","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In Greek mythology, 'Macareus' was one of the Heliadae, sons of Helios and\nRhodos. Macareus and his brothers, Triopas, Actis and Candalus, were jealous of\na fifth brother, Tenages's, skill at science, so they killed him and had to\nescape from Rhodes upon discovery of their crime. (The two Heliadae Ochimus and\nCercaphus stayed aside and remained on the island of Rhodes). Diodorus\nSiculus, Library of History, 5. 57. 2\n\nMacareus fled to Lesbos, where he became king, and took over many of the\nneighboring islands. Lesbos, son of Lapithes and grandson of Aeolus, after whom\nthe island came to be named, married Macareus' daughter, Methymna (eponym of\nMethymna, a city at Lesbos); Diodorus Siculus, Library of History, 5.\n81 alternately, Methymna married Lepetymnus, eponym of a mountain on\nLesbos, Stephanus of Byzantium, s. v. Methymna and had by him two\nsons, Hicetaon and Hypsipylus, who were slain by Achilles during the sack of the\ncity of Methymna. Parthenius, Love Romances, 21 Among Macareus' other\ndaughters were Mytilene, Agamede, Antissa, and Arisbe, all eponyms of cities at\nLesbos. Stephanus of Byzantium, ss. vv. Mytilene; Agamede; Antissa;\nArisbe His sons were entrusted by him the leadership of the colonies he\nfounded on the neighbouring islands: Cydrolaus was sent to Samos, Neandrus to\nCos, Leucippus to Rhodes (where the colonists mixed with the local population),\nand an unnamed son to Chios. Diodorus Siculus, Library of History, 5. 81.\n8 Yet another son of Macareus, Eresus, gave his name to a town on Lesbos\n(modern Eresos). Stephanus of Byzantium s. v. Eresos\n","linknr":128,"url":"Macareus_(son_of_Helios)","recorded":1374548291,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Macareus_(son_of_Helios)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Macareus_(son_of_Helios)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommon